All three techniques run at well over 100 FPS on the test machine. Shadow maps have the lowest GPU cost but require 16 MB of texture memory and an extra depth pass. Shadow volumes have the highest GPU cost (3.13 ms vs 1.97 ms) due to fill rate, but use only 2.1 MB and produce hard, alias-free shadows without any bias parameter. Ambient occlusion sits in between in GPU cost (2.24 ms) but has no memory overhead and no directional shadowing ability. The benchmark can be regenerated with:node scripts/capture-shadow-benchmarks.mjs

KNOWN BUGS AND LIMITATIONS
- Shadow maps cast only from/onto terrain cubes; custom entity and creature
    shaders do not yet sample the shadow map texture.
- Shadow volumes use a finite extrusion distance rather than true homogeneous
    infinity, because WebGL does not expose desktop-style depth clamp. The far
    cap may fail for very shallow sun angles.
- Both advanced techniques produce hard shadows only. Shadow maps include a
    3x3 PCF pass that approximates soft edges; volumes do not.
- The gameplay layer is functional for the demo, but the creature roster
    covers only three starter types (15 species). Expansion to all 18 planned
    types and deeper balance tuning remain future work.
- Wild creature AI uses simple wander/flee behavior without pathfinding.

